					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8530826#post-4058677</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8530826/scp-4988#post-4058677</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Wed, 14 Nov 2018 18:11:42 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>The LolMe</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>2162634</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>At this point, those could be just shell clones of the original. But I also don't feel much risk of a breach.</p> <p>On the other hand, if the call center had an aggresive marketing campaing and threatened to monopolize the call center service I would agree on the keter classification.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8530826#post-4058675</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8530826/scp-4988#post-4058675</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Wed, 14 Nov 2018 18:08:31 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>The LolMe</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>2162634</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>If I'm reading this correctly, Restwynn Security Installations isn't anomalous; the outsourced call center is. Also, shouldn't APP Inc investigation be top priority? they're the anomalous entity here from what I get.</p> <p>If that's correct, the Containment Procedures make no sense since the Foundation is just dumping a non-anomalous company while the SCP can just contact other possible clients (implied in the last addendum?).</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
